{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ccd42cdc-31a7-4968-b284-780a94090128","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**`datetime.now()` on line 3** — called directly inside the view, making it hard to mock in tests since you can't freeze or inject the time.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `timezone.now()` (timezone-aware) and inject it so tests can override it:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request, now_func=timezone.now):\n    now = now_func()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nOr, if you prefer not to change signatures, use the popular **`freezegun`** library in tests:\n\n```python\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-05-08\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    response = self.client.get(\"/\")\n    ...\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| File | Line | Call | Issue |\n|------|------|------|-------|\n| `views.py` | 3 | `datetime.now()` | Not timezone-aware, not injectable |\n\nThis is a small project — only one static call found. The fix is straightforward: switch to `django.utils.timezone.now` and use `freezegun` or dependency injection for testability.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"14ada2b7-b028-463b-bb99-04b878c85cba","outputTokens":304,"requestId":"67CC:26153C:301D487:354C610:69FD4FFC"},"id":"04052c98-5353-4ae0-b125-4d0d9d50d09c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T02:52:52.643Z","parentId":"0f9764b7-62bf-49bb-b0f0-450011a149fc"}
